The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal
		 Friday, July 30, 2004  BRIEFS
				 																																	Calcutta, July 29: Mamata Banerjee today threatened to paralyse Bengal for three days if the government tried to foil the 12-hour bandh she has called on Monday. 				 																																	The CPM is planning to create terror and pass the buck to our party, she said. The Trinamul Congress is opposing the block-level pre-litigation bill that allows settlement of civil disputes outside court.				 																																	Calcutta: The chief minister told the Assembly on Thursday that no meritorious student would be denied higher education for want of money. If such students cannot afford loans, they can come to us. I am appealing to MLAs that if they know students who are poor but have done well and want to continue studying, they can come to my office or ask the students to write to me, Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee said.				 																																	Balagarh (Hooghly): The widow of Khitish Mukherjee, a high school teacher here, 60 km from Calcutta, was taken by surprise when she received a cheque for Rs 1,81,837. Shantikana, 73, lost her husband on March 19,1970. She got her pension on Wednesday.				 																																	Calcutta: Soma Mandal, a bank officers wife, apparently committed suicide after strangulating her 11-month son at Baruipur in South 24-Parganas. Sanjay, the husband, found them dead on returning home. Police have detained him.
